      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) match simulation boundary conditions within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Benchtop loop experiments were conducted at 23±0.5°C using porcine blood analog (glycerol-water, viscosity 3.5±0.1 mPa·s). Flow rates were set via calibrated Coriolis meter (±1.5%). Rotational speed was controlled via servo drive (±5 RPM). All experimental parameters were mapped to CFD boundary conditions within their respective uncertainty intervals. Test conditions assessed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH within 15% of experimental measurements across all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values compared against experimental measurements at all 5 flow-speed combinations. Maximum relative error was 11.7% at the 3 L/min / 2500 RPM point; mean absolute relative error was 7.3%. All predictions fall within the 15% acceptance band. Output comparison assessed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation QoIs (NIH, volume-averaged shear stress, RH index) are directly linked to the clinical hemolysis decision criterion.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI, normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), is the established regulatory metric for blood pump hemolysis assessment (FDA guidance 2017). The relative hemolysis index RH directly supports the predicate comparison decision. Volume-averaged shear stress is an intermediate QoI used for model diagnostics. All QoIs are clinically and regulatorily relevant to the CPB hemolysis decision. Assessed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
